Abstract

This BLAPER is a bridge between two communities that often talk past each other. In revealed preference, Afriat/Varian tools are a gold standard for rationalizing demand with minimal structure. In modern AI, prompting and in-context learning are a pragmatic way to elicit predictions without committing to a full parametric model.

We take a canonical lab dataset — a repeated portfolio-choice experiment with ambiguity — and turn it into two prediction games. Afriat yields a disciplined, nonparametric set-valued counterfactual; narrative prompts produce a human-readable procedural rule that selects a point. The headline message is:

Afriat is a constraint; narratives are a selector. Afriat tells you what choices are consistent with concave utility; a narrative rule tells you which choice the person tends to make.

Reading guide

If you come from revealed preference:

  • §3 explains the prediction games and why prompts are a measurement device.
  • §4.2 reframes narrative prompting as model selection over interpretable procedures.
  • §5.3 is where point prediction forces Afriat to choose a point (tie-breakers).

If you come from LLMs / AI:

  • §4.1 explains Afriat and why it produces sets (correspondences).
  • §5.1 is the set-diagnostics dashboard: coverage/width/distance.
  • §7 gives prompt templates, output constraints, and evaluation conventions.

1. Why this BLAPER exists

In one sentence: rationalization is not prediction. Revealed preference tells us that many datasets are consistent with some concave utility — but when you ask “what will this person do under a new price vector?”, the honest Afriat answer is often: “a set of things.”

Meanwhile, modern AI often starts from the opposite direction: we can get strong conditional predictions out of a model, but the object can be opaque. When the target is a human decision, we would like something in between: a prediction method that is (i) disciplined, (ii) interpretable, and (iii) honest about uncertainty.

Our move is to treat “procedure” as first-class. The narrative prompts are not a gimmick; they are a way to surface the implicit decision procedure of a subject (equal-dollar? memory-based? price-sensitive?) while keeping a tight link to the original economic objects.

2. Data & experiment (with provenance)

2.1 Provenance (quick)

Source: Ahn, Choi, Gale & Kariv (2014), Quantitative Economics. Subjects allocate wealth across three Arrow securities (three states). One state's probability is known (1/3); the other two are ambiguous (unknown to subjects) and sum to 2/3.

Expand: protocol details (from the paper)
  • Where / who: Experimental Social Science Laboratory (Xlab), UC Berkeley; 154 subjects recruited from undergraduates and staff.
  • Rounds: 50 independent decision problems per subject, presented via a graphical “point-and-click” budget interface.
  • Budget sets: each round draws a random budget set with intercepts between 0 and 100 tokens, and at least one intercept > 50 tokens; budget sets are independent across rounds and subjects.
  • Discretization: resolution compatibility is 0.2 tokens (this creates small budget slack in the cleaned CSV).
  • Payment: at the end, one round is randomly selected for payment (equal probability across rounds). The paper converts tokens to dollars at a fixed rate (token value reported as \$0.50).
  • Ambiguity implementation note (paper footnote): in practice one ambiguous state's probability is drawn from a uniform distribution and the other is the remainder, but this distribution is not revealed to subjects.

2.2 How the cleaned CSV encodes a budget

We use rationalitydata3goods.csv (7700 rows = 154×50). Each row is a (subject, trial) with chosen quantities x,y,z, intercepts xa,ya,za, and prices px,py,pz.

The key identity is p ≈ 100 / intercept. Intuitively: if xa is the maximum quantity of X you could buy with budget 100, then the per-unit price is px = 100/xa.

Expand: why there is “cash leftover”
The original interface restricts choices to a discrete grid (resolution compatibility ≈ 0.2 tokens). When we compute dollar spend p·x from the cleaned file, the budget may not be hit exactly due to rounding. We treat the residual as cash: cash = 100 − (px·x + py·y + pz·z). In this dataset the median slack is about $0.28 on a $100 budget.

3. Two prediction games

The raw data is a sequence of choice problems. To turn it into an AI-style benchmark we define two “games” that differ only in how much history you are allowed to see.

Two prediction games. Task A is a one-step forecast. Task B is early-history generalization (harder).

3.1 Task A: one-step prediction (t=1..49 → t=50)

You see a subject’s first 49 trials: prices and realized dollar allocations. Then you are shown the true price vector at trial 50 and asked to predict the allocation. This is the simplest out-of-sample test: 49→50.

Expand: what makes this hard for Afriat
Afriat naturally outputs a set-valued prediction (a correspondence). To produce a point forecast, you must add a tie-breaker / selection rule. In §5.3 we compare several Afriat point variants to narrative rule selection.

3.2 Task B: early-history generalization (t=1..25 → t=26..50)

Here the model gets only the first half of the subject’s history (trials 1..25). We then evaluate how well it generalizes to later price vectors (26..50). This is closer to the kind of generalization you want if you treat the first half of the experiment as “training” and the second half as “future behavior”.

In this BLAPER, the Afriat set dashboard focuses on the hardest single counterfactual: t=50 using early history t=1..25. For a concrete multi-step view, §6 includes a per-period error time series for Subject 920 over t=26..50.

4. Methods (Afriat meets prompting)

4.1 Afriat for AI readers: a disciplined set

Think of Afriat as a feasibility program: does there exist a concave utility that rationalizes these choices? If yes, you can construct an Afriat utility.

For a new price vector, the Afriat utility implies a set of maximizers — the demand correspondence. That is the core reason Afriat predictions are often set-valued.

Expand: how we evaluate an Afriat set without picking a point
We project the correspondence onto one coordinate at a time (one stock’s dollar spend). This yields a projected band [min,max]. We report:
  • Coverage: does the truth lie inside the band?
  • Band width: how informative is the band?
  • Distance-to-band: if outside, how far is the miss?
This keeps Afriat honest: we do not force a point forecast unless we are explicitly in Task A (§5.3).

4.2 Prompting for RP readers: procedures as models

A narrative prompt turns a subject’s history into a compact story and asks for the next allocation. But the modeling object is not the prose — it is the rule library.

We define a small menu of interpretable candidate procedures (equal-dollar, equal-share, kNN memory, power-share, dominance). For each subject we select the best rule by cross-validation on that subject’s own history.

Expand: rule library (explicit definitions)

We keep the narrative side intentionally interpretable by restricting to a small rule library. Each rule maps prices (pX,pY,pZ) to a dollar allocation (sX,sY,sZ).

  • Equal-dollar: sX=sY=sZ=100/3.
  • Equal-share: equalize quantities; in dollars this implies s_i ∝ p_i so s_i = 100·p_i/(pX+pY+pZ).
  • Power-share: s_i = 100·w_i with w_i ∝ p_i^{-α}. α controls price sensitivity (α=0 gives equal-dollar).
  • kNN memory: find the K most similar past price vectors; predict as a (possibly weighted) average of their historical allocations.
  • Dominance: allocate (nearly) all budget to a single stock (e.g., the cheapest).

The goal is not to “win Kaggle”. The goal is to produce a procedure you can read and then compare it to Afriat’s disciplined feasibility set.

Expand: why this is a useful “foundation-model probe”
We deliberately tell the model “you are an investor” and give the history as a time-labeled journey. This activates generic priors (budgeting, diversification, chasing the cheap asset, inertia) while keeping the task grounded: the only numerical inputs are prices and past allocations, and the output must satisfy the budget. The goal is to see whether a foundation model can infer a plausible procedure, not just interpolate.

5. Results

5.1 Afriat set diagnostics at t=50 (train t=1..25)

We fit Afriat with observation-specific slack δt using trials 1..25. At t=50 we compute the implied Afriat correspondence, project it to a 1D band for each stock, and report coverage/width/distance.

“Narrative better | outside” = fraction of outside-band cases where the narrative point is closer than the nearest Afriat-feasible value.

5.2 Narrative heterogeneity (procedural types)

Using only early history (t=1..25), we select a best-fitting narrative rule family per subject. The distribution is not trivial: a large fraction look smooth and price-responsive, but many look like equal-dollar allocators or memory-based case reasoning.

Narrative family (selected using t=1..25) Count Share
Power-share (smooth) 61 39.6%
Case-based (kNN memory) 41 26.6%
Equal-dollar 34 22.1%
Equal-share 13 8.4%
Dominance (all-in) 5 3.2%

The point is not that any rule is “true”, but that the data supports multiple distinct procedures.

Narrative family counts (train t=1..25).

5.3 Task A point prediction (train t=1..49 → predict t=50)

Here we force everyone to play the same counterfactual game: given a new price vector, predict the realized allocation. Narrative rules are naturally point-valued. Afriat must be converted to a point using tie-breakers / discretization / slack variants.

7. Prompting details (templates + evaluation)

The narrative prompt is designed to do two things: (i) make the task legible to a general-purpose LLM (“you are an investor…”), and (ii) keep the output machine-checkable (JSON only).

Expand: Task A prompt template (49→50) 
Investor Journey — Subject {ID}

You are an investor running a repeated portfolio-allocation exercise.
There are 3 stocks. Each trial you receive a fresh $100 and allocate it across these stocks.
Ignore macro considerations; focus only on this portfolio/journey of decisions.

Stocks:
  - PapayaTech (ticker: X)
  - AxolotlWorks (ticker: Y)
  - QuipuQuantum (ticker: Z)

Your past 49 trials (t = 1..49):
t=01 prices: X=$..., Y=$..., Z=$... | spend: X=$..., Y=$..., Z=$... | cash=$...
...
t=49 prices: X=$..., Y=$..., Z=$... | spend: X=$..., Y=$..., Z=$... | cash=$...

Now the 50th trial arrives.
t=50 prices: X=$pX50, Y=$pY50, Z=$pZ50

Return ONLY a single JSON object:
{"PapayaTech": 0.00, "AxolotlWorks": 0.00, "QuipuQuantum": 0.00, "Cash": 0.00}
Expand: Task B prompt template (1..25 → 26..50) 
Investor Journey — Subject {ID}

(History)
t=01 ... 
...
t=25 ...

(Forecast block)
For each future trial t=26..50 you are given the prices. Predict the allocation for each t.

Output ONLY JSON with one record per t:
[
  {"t": 26, "PapayaTech": 0.00, "AxolotlWorks": 0.00, "QuipuQuantum": 0.00, "Cash": 0.00},
  ...
  {"t": 50, "PapayaTech": 0.00, "AxolotlWorks": 0.00, "QuipuQuantum": 0.00, "Cash": 0.00}
]
Expand: evaluation conventions (why “JSON only”)
Prompt evaluation breaks down if outputs are not parseable. We therefore require a strict JSON schema and project the model’s output onto the budget (cash is set to the residual). This makes the benchmark robust to stylistic verbosity while keeping the economics clean.

8. Glossary (hover-enabled)

Terms in the text with dotted underlines can be hovered for definitions. This section lists all definitions in one place.

Arrow security
A state-contingent asset: it pays 1 unit if a particular state occurs and 0 otherwise. The experiment uses three such securities (three states).
Ambiguity
Uncertainty about probabilities (not just uncertainty about outcomes). In the experiment, one state's probability is known; the other two are intentionally not revealed.
GARP
Generalized Axiom of Revealed Preference. No revealed-preference cycles; a nonparametric test for concave utility rationalizability.
Afriat inequalities
Linear inequalities whose feasibility is equivalent to GARP. A feasible solution constructs a concave utility that rationalizes the observed choices.
Afriat utility
The piecewise-linear concave utility recovered from a feasible solution of the Afriat inequalities. It rationalizes the observed dataset.
Demand correspondence
At a price vector, the set of utility-maximizing bundles. For piecewise-linear utilities, this set can be a face (many maximizers), not a single point.
Slack (δ, δ_t)
Additive relaxations when exact Afriat inequalities are infeasible (due to noise/discretization). δ is global; δ_t is observation-specific.
Set-valued prediction
A prediction that is a set of feasible behaviors (e.g., all bundles consistent with Afriat utility), not a single point.
Projected band
For a fixed counterfactual price and one stock, the interval [min,max] of feasible counterfactual dollar spend on that stock implied by the Afriat correspondence after projection.
Coverage
Share of subjects whose realized counterfactual spend lies inside the projected band.
Distance-to-band
If the truth lies outside the band, the absolute distance to the nearest endpoint; 0 if inside.
Band width
max − min of the projected band. Narrow bands are informative but may miss the truth; wide bands may cover the truth but be uninformative.
Price dispersion
Here: max(pX,pY,pZ) / min(pX,pY,pZ). High dispersion tends to induce corner/near-corner choices.
Prompt
Structured text given to an LLM: context + task instruction + required output format. Here, the prompt is a subject’s investment 'journey' and the final question asks for the next allocation.
In-context learning
When a model adapts its behavior from examples and structure inside the prompt, without updating model weights.
Narrative rule
A compact, interpretable procedure mapping prices to allocations (e.g., equal-dollar, kNN memory, power-share), inferred from a subject’s history.
Rule library
The finite menu of candidate narrative rules. Personalization happens by selecting which rule best fits each subject.
Cross-validation
Model selection using held-out periods: fit/select on part of the history, evaluate on unseen periods from the same subject.
kNN memory
Case-based rule: find past trials with similar price vectors (nearest neighbors) and reuse/average the corresponding allocations.
Power-share rule
Smooth heuristic allocating shares as a power function of relative prices, capturing substitution patterns without a full parametric utility.
Equal-dollar
Heuristic that splits the $100 equally across the three stocks, regardless of prices.
Equal-share
Heuristic that equalizes quantities (shares) across stocks; in dollar terms, this tilts spending toward higher-priced stocks.
Dominance (all-in)
Heuristic that places nearly all budget into a single stock (e.g., cheapest or historically favored).
Tie-breaker
A selection rule used when Afriat yields multiple maximizers; e.g., choose the maximizer closest to a historical 'anchor' allocation.
One-step prediction (49→50)
Use trials 1..49 to predict the subject’s allocation at trial 50 given the real trial-50 prices.
Early-history generalization (1..25→26..50)
Use only the first half of history to predict choices under later price vectors (a harder generalization test).
L1 error
Sum of absolute dollar errors across the three stock spends at a target trial (here typically t=50).
Top-asset accuracy
Whether the model correctly predicts which stock receives the largest spend at the target trial.
Near all-in
A trial is 'near all-in' if the maximum spend across stocks is at least $90.

References
